    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The default value of this property is "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "nil"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", which causes the layer to use a standard shadow shape. If you specify a value for this property, the layer creates its shadow using the specified path instead of the layer’s composited alpha channel. The path you provide defines the outline of the shadow. It is filled using the non-zero winding rule and the current shadow color, opacity, and blur radius. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Unlike most animatable properties, this property (as with all "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "CGPathRef"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " animatable properties) does not support implicit animation. However, the path object may be animated using any of the concrete subclasses of "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/quartzcore/capropertyanimation"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". Paths will interpolate as a linear blend of the \"on-line\" points; \"off-line\" points may be interpolated non-linearly (to preserve continuity of the curve's derivative). If the two paths have a different number of control points or segments, the results are undefined. If the path extends outside the layer bounds it will not automatically be clipped to the layer, only if the normal layer masking rules cause that."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Specifying an explicit path usually improves rendering performance."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The value of this property is retained using the Core Foundation retain/release semantics. This behavior occurs despite the fact that the property declaration appears to use the default assign semantics for object retention. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Using Shadow Path for Special Effects",
          "anchor": "2851605"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can use a layer's shadow path to create special effects such as simulating the shadows available in "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "title": "Pages",
              "destination": "http://www.apple.com/pages/"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
